nment Brigade]]\n|awards        = [[File:Bronze Star ribbon.svg|30px]] [[Bronze Star Medal|Bronze Star]]<br>[[File:Meritorious Service ribbon.svg|30px]] [[Meritorious Service Medal (United States)|Meritorious Service]]<br>[[File:Army Commendation Medal ribbon.svg|30px]] [[Commendation Medal|Army Commendation Medal]]<br>[[File:Army Reserve Achievement ribbon.svg|30px]] [[Reserve Good Conduct Medal|Reserve Good Conduct]]<br>[[File:National Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|30px]] [[National Defense Service Medal]]\n}}\n'''Steven Ernst \"Steve\" Stivers''' (born March 24, 1965) is an [[United States|American]] politician who has been the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|OH|15}}<ref name=\"http://www.cnn.com\">[http://www.cnn.com/ELECTION/2010/results/individual/#OHH15]</ref> since 2011. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. Stivers previously served in the [[Ohio Senate]], representing the 16th district. He is a [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]] in the [[Ohio Army National Guard]] and served [[active duty]] in [[Iraq]] as [[Battalion#United States Army and Marine Corps|Battalion]] [[Commanding officer|Commander]] until December 2005.\n\n==Early life, education, and career==\n\nStivers was born and grew up in [[Ripley, Ohio]], the son of Carol Sue (n\u00e9e Pulliam) and Ernst Bambach Stivers.<ref>http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/%7Ebattle/reps/stivers.htm</ref> Steve is a recipient of the [[Eagle Scout (Boy Scouts of America)|Eagle Scout]] Award.<ref name=\"trivillagerotary.org\">[http://www.trivillagerotary.org/Newsletters/2008/3-26-08.doc]</ref>\n\nStivers attended The [[Ohio State University]] where he earned a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in [[economics]] and [[international relations]] in 1989 and an [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] in 1996.<ref name=\"test2\">[http://www.stivers4congress.com/?q=biography Steve Stivers Biography]</ref> While attending Ohio State he joined the [[Delta Upsilon]] Fraternity.\n\nStivers spent seven years at [[Bank One]], three years at the Ohio Company, two years as Finance Director for the [[Franklin County, Ohio|Franklin County]] Republican Party and five years as a staff member in the [[Ohio Senate]].<ref name=about>{{cite web\n  | title = Senator Steve Stivers - Website\n  | work =\n  | publisher =\n  | date =\n  | url = http://www.senatorstevestivers.com/index.php?id=33\n  | doi =\n  | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080411022148/www.senatorstevestivers.com/about/\n  | archivedate= 2008-04-11\n  | accessdate = 2009-10-28}}</ref> Stivers has worked as a [[General Securities Representative Exam|Series 7]] licensed securities [[stockbroker|trader]] with the Ohio Company.<ref name=\"about\"/>\n\n==Military service==\nStivers has served in the [[Ohio Army National Guard]] since 1985 and holds the rank of Colonel in the [[United States Army Logistics Branch|Logistics branch]]. Stivers was called to [[active duty]] while serving in the Ohio Senate in October 2004. It was then that Stivers served in [[Iraq]], [[Kuwait]], [[Qatar]], and [[Djibouti]] as Battalion Commander until December 2005. He was awarded a [[Bronze Star]] for his accomplishments as a battalion commander during [[Operation Iraqi Freedom]].<ref name=about/>\n\n==Ohio Senate==\n\n===Elections===\nAfter redistricting, incumbent Republican [[Priscilla Mead]] decided to resign after only serving in the [[Ohio Senate]] for a year.<ref>http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=cgskAAAAIBAJ&sjid=wxIEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3556,12300&dq=priscilla+mead&hl=en</ref> Stivers was the \"compromise candidate\" after a Senate screening committee could not agree on him and fellow State Representative [[Jim Hughes (politician)|Jim Hughes]], who were both running for the district.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/elections/candidates/steve-stivers-57257 | work=Fox News | title=Steve Stivers | deadurl=yes}} {{Dead link|date=June 2012|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref> Stivers won a special election in January 2003 unopposed.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=29789</ref> He then won re-election in 2004 to a full senate term with 58% of the vote.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=70709</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nStivers served in the [[Ohio Senate]] from January 9, 2003 until December 2008.\n\n;Legislation\nHe sponsored 12 bills while in office which became law, 11 of which were bipartisan.<ref name=\"trivillagerotary.org\"/> He was the lead sponsor of the following bills: <br />\n- A comprehensive [[tort]] reform bill which was enacted in 2004.<ref name=\"test2\"/> \n* Allowed members of the Armed Forces Reserves who are called to active duty to defer paying property taxes during the length of a deployment.<ref name=test2/> \n* Provided doctors limited civil protections if they choose to give free care to uninsured people, resulting in more than $1 million of free care in Franklin County alone.<ref name=test2/> \n* Worked to ensure those with disabilities in need of healthcare have the option to buy into Ohio\u2019s Medicaid system.<ref name=test2/> \n* Worked to strengthen Ohio's sex offender laws.<ref name=test2/>\n\nHe also passed a balanced, fiscally conservative state budget, provided the largest personal property tax cut in Ohio history, and froze tuition rates for Ohio\u2019s college students.<ref name=test2/>\n\n===Committee assignments===\nSenator Stivers sat on a variety of Ohio Senate committees. He was the Chairman of the Insurance, Commerce and Labor Committee, Vice-Chair of the Finance and Financial Institutions Committee, served on the Ways and Means Committee, the Judiciary Committee on Civil Justice, the Judiciary Committee for Criminal Justice, and also the Controlling Board.<ref>[http://www.freedomspeaks.com/official/63247/ohio-%28oh%29-state-senator-steve-stivers-%5Boh-senate%5D Freedom Speaks Official Profile]</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;2008\n[[Image:StiversGrandviewParade.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Steve Stivers shaking hands at the Grandview Memorial Day Weekend Parade.]]\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Ohio, 2008#District 15}}\n\nIn November 2007, Stivers announced he would run for election to Congress in Ohio's 15th District, a seat held by retiring Republican member [[Deborah Pryce]]. He won the Republican nomination and ran against Democratic nominee Mary Jo Kilroy, [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]] Mark Noble and Independent Don Elijah Eckhart. Stivers lost by 2,311 votes, conceding on December 7, 2008 after a long vote  recount.\n\n;2010\n[[File:Boehnerandstivers.jpg|thumb|[[John Boehner]], the then House Minority Leader, campaigning for fellow Ohio Congressman Steve Stivers (left) during the [[United States House of Representatives elections in Ohio, 2010|2010 midterm elections]]|right|alt=]]\n{{See also |United States House of Representatives elections in Ohio, 2010#District 15*}}\n\nStivers won the Republican primary with 82% of the vote.<ref>http://vote.franklincountyohio.gov/assets/pdf/2010/primary/EL45A.HTM</ref>\n<ref>[http://www.dispatchpolitics.com/live/content/local_news/stories/2010/05/05/copy/dailey-gibbs-fight-for-lead-in-gops-18th.html?adsec=politics&sid=101]</ref> He again faced Democratic incumbent [[Mary Jo Kilroy]] along with Constitution Party nominee David Ryon and Libertarian nominee William J. Kammerer. November 2, 2010 Kilroy conceded to Stivers.\n\n'''2012'''<br />\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Ohio, 2012#District 15}}\nStivers ran again in 2012 against Democratic nominee Pat Lang.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ohio Secretary of State|url=http://www.sos.state.oh.us/sos/upload/elections/2012/gen/UScongress.pdf}}</ref>  He was endorsed by the NRA, National Right to Life, Ohio State Medical Association and United States Chamber of Commerce. Stivers was re-elected by 76,397 votes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Stivers for Congress|url=http://www.stivers4congress.com/endorsements}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\n\n;Budget\nStivers has voted against raising the debt limit when there was no offset or systemic reform and supports prioritizing spending in the event that the debt limit is reached.<ref name=issues>{{cite web| title =Steve Stivers: (Republican, district 15) | work =On the Issues| url =http://www.ontheissues.org/OH/Steve_Stivers.htm}}</ref><ref name=votebudget>{{cite web| title =Representative Steve Stivers's Voting Records: Budget, Spending and Taxes| work =Vote Smart| url =http://votesmart.org/candidate/key-votes/45333/steve-stivers/10/budget-spending-and-taxes#.UcC4mvk3upo}}</ref>  He was part of a proposal to add a balanced budget amendment to the US Constitution.<ref name=issues/><ref name=votebudget/>  Stivers voted to offset the costs of disaster relief spending through discretionary budget cuts.<ref name=votebudget/>\n\nOn April 25, 2013, Stivers introduced a bill that would alter the composition of the [[Penny (United States coin)|penny]], [[Nickel (United States coin)|nickel]], [[Dime (United States coin)|dime]] and [[Quarter (United States coin)|quarter]] to [[steel]] with a [[copper]] coat, which would save an estimated $433,000,000 over the course of ten years.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bill Seeks Steel Cents, Nickels, Dimes, and Quarters|author=Zielinski, M.|url=http://news.coinupdate.com/bill-seeks-steel-cents-nickels-dimes-and-quarters-1952/|newspaper=Coin Update|date=April 29, 2013|accessdate=May 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe voted to audit the Federal Reserve and its recent actions, specifically its involvement in mortgage loans.<ref name=issues/>\n\n;Energy\nStivers supports all energy options, including green, nuclear, and clean coal and supports tax benefits for renewable energy usage.<ref name=issues/><ref name=voteeenergy>{{cite web| title =Representative Steve Stivers's Voting Records: Energy| work =Vote Smart| url =http://votesmart.org/candidate/key-votes/45333/steve-stivers/29/energy#.UcC8rvk3upo}}</ref>  However Stivers opposes federal regulations on efficiency standards<ref name=issues/>\n\n;Gun Control\nStivers is a strong supporter of gun rights and opposes any limits to Second Amendment rights.<ref name=issues/>  He supports loosening regulations for interstate gun purchases and supports veterans registering unlicensed firearms acquired from outside the United States.<ref name=issues/>\n\n;Healthcare\nStivers is an opponent of government-run healthcare and has voted on numerous occasions against such.<ref name=issues/><ref name=votehealth>{{cite web| title =Representative Steve Stivers's Voting Records: Health and Healthcare| work =Vote Smart| url =http://votesmart.org/candidate/key-votes/45333/steve-stivers/38/health-and-health-care#.UcDB6_k3upo}}</ref>  He supports privatized healthcare options opposes the use of federal funds for any healthcare program expansions or acts.<ref name=issues/><ref name=votehealth/>\n\n;Social Security\nRep. Stivers opposes the privatization of social security.<ref name=issues/>  In addition, he also opposes raising the retirement age from its current state.<ref name=issues/>\n\n;Taxes\nStivers took the Taxpayer Protection pledge, insuring he would not support any tax raises.<ref name=issues/>  He supports a flat federal tax rate across the board for all income brackets.<ref name=issues/>\n\n===Legislation===\nOn November 21, 2013, Stivers introduced the bill [[To amend the Federal Home Loan Bank Act to authorize privately insured credit unions to become members of a Federal home loan bank (H.R. 3584; 113th Congress)]].<ref name=3584sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 3584 - Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/3584|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=4 May 2014}}</ref> The bill would amend the [[Federal Home Loan Bank Act]] to treat certain privately insured [[credit union]]s as insured depository institutions for purposes of determining eligibility for membership in a federal home loan bank.<ref name=\"3584sum\"/> The bill was scheduled to be voted on under a [[suspension of the rules]] on May 6, 2014.<ref name=HouseExIRS>{{cite news|last=Marcos|first=Cristina|title=The week ahead: House to hold ex-IRS official in contempt|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/scheduling/205099-the-week-ahead-house-to-hold-ex-irs-official-in-contempt|accessdate=5 May 2014|newspaper=The Hill|date=2 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Financial Services|Committee on Financial Services]]'''\n**[[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Capital Markets and Government-Sponsored Enterprises|Subcommittee on Capital Markets and Government-Sponsored Enterprises]]\n**[[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Insurance, Housing and Community Opportunity|Subcommittee on Insurance, Housing and Community Opportunity]]\n\n*[[Republican Study Committee]]\n*[[Republican Main Street Partnership]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n*Congressional Arts Caucus\n\n==Electoral history==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable collapsible\"\n|-bgcolor=#cccccc\n!colspan=24 style=\"background: #ccccff;\" |Election results<ref>{{cite news | first = | last =  | title = Election Results | date = | url = http://www.sos.state.oh.us/elections/Research/electResultsMain.aspx | work = Ohio Secretary of State | accessdate = 2014-03-01}}</ref>\n|-\n!'''Year'''\n!'''Office'''\n!'''Election'''\n!\n!'''Subject'''\n!'''Party'''\n!'''Votes'''\n!'''%'''\n!\n!'''Opponent'''\n!'''Party'''\n!'''Votes'''\n!'''%'''\n!\n!'''Opponent'''\n!'''Party'''\n!'''Votes'''\n!'''%'''\n!\n!'''Opponent'''\n!'''Party'''\n!'''Votes'''\n!'''%'''\n!\n|-\n|2004\n|[[Ohio Senate]]\n|[[General election (U.S.)|General]]\n|\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |'''Steve Stivers'''\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |95,251\n|{{Party shading/Republica